<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Due process for institutions and programs. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) To be listed by the Secretary as a nationally recognized accrediting agency, an accrediting agency must demonstrate
to the Secretary that the procedures it uses throughout the accrediting process satisfy due process requirements.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) The Secretary considers that an accrediting agency's procedures satisfy due process requirements if_
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) The agency sets forth in writing its procedures governing its accreditation or preaccreditation processes;

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) The agency's procedures afford an institution or program a reasonable period of time to comply with agency requests
for information and documents; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) The agency notifies the institution or program in writing of any adverse accrediting action; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(4) The agency's notice describes with particularity the basis for any adverse accrediting action; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(5) The agency permits the institution or program the opportunity to appeal an adverse accrediting action, and the
right to representation by counsel during an appeal, except that the agency, at its sole discretion, may limit the
appeal to a written appeal; and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(6) The agency notifies the applicant in writing of the result of the appeal and the basis for that result.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

